y:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list\">link</a>) CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list\">link</a>) </span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Cresswell &amp; Spandler (2013). \"The Engaged Academic: Academic Intellectuals and the Psychiatric Survivor Movement\". <i><a href=\"/wiki/Social_Movement_Studies\" title=\"Social Movement Studies\">Social Movement Studies</a></i>. <b>12</b> (2): 138\u2013154.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Social+Movement+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=The+Engaged+Academic%3A+Academic+Intellectuals+and+the+Psychiatric+Survivor+Movement&amp;rft.volume=12&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=138-154&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.au=Cresswell+%26+Spandler&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMad+studies\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:1-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Ingram, Richard A. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://journals.library.mun.ca/ojs/index.php/IJ/article/view/1680/1327\">\"Doing Mad Studies: Making (Non)sense Together\"</a>. <i>Intersectionalities</i>. <b>5</b> (3 (Special Issue) Mad Studies: Intersections with Disability Studies, Social Work, and \u2018Mental Health\u2019): 11\u201317.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_